<answer>Using trigonometry, we can find the coordinates of the new point after the rotation. The given point is in the first quadrant, and we're rotating it by $60^\circ$ counter-clockwise. Using the rotation formulas, we get

 \begin{align*}
x' &= 4 + 7 \sqrt{3} \cos 60^\circ - 7 \sin 60^\circ \\
y' &= 7 - 4 \sqrt{3} \cos 60^\circ - 4 \sin 60^\circ
\end{align*}

Since $\cos 60^\circ = \frac{1}{2}$ and $\sin 60^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$, we have

 \begin{align*}
x' &= 4 + 7 \sqrt{3} \cdot \frac{1}{2} - 7 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
y' &= 7 - 4 \sqrt{3} \cdot \frac{1}{2} - 4 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{align*}

Simplifying,

 \begin{align*}
x' &= 4 - 7 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} + \frac{7 \sqrt{3}}{2} \\
y' &= 7 - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2 \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}

We can combine like terms,

 \begin{align*}
x' &= 4 \\
y' &= 7 - 4 \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}

So the new point after a $60^\circ$ counter-clockwise rotation is $\boxed{(4, 7 - 4 \sqrt{3})}$.
</answer>

